{"parse":{"title":"Freedom of testation","pageid":26149775,"revid":843150198,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>Freedom of testation</b> is the power of a person to make a <a href=\"/wiki/Will_and_testament\" title=\"Will and testament\">will and testament</a> specifying whatever heirs they please. It is historically associated with English <a href=\"/wiki/Common_law\" title=\"Common law\">common law</a>, and contrasted with <a href=\"/wiki/Forced_heirship\" title=\"Forced heirship\">forced heirship</a>, where part or all of the estate is automatically inherited by the <a href=\"/wiki/Next_of_kin\" title=\"Next of kin\">next of kin</a>. Opponents of absolute freedom of testation have pointed to the possibility of a widow or orphan being left destitute while property of a spouse or parent is bequeathed to others. Some opponents of <a href=\"/wiki/Inheritance_tax\" title=\"Inheritance tax\">inheritance tax</a> have characterized it as an abrogation of freedom of testation.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"History\">History</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Freedom_of_testation&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: History\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>After the <a href=\"/wiki/Norman_conquest_of_England\" title=\"Norman conquest of England\">Norman conquest of England</a>, the <a href=\"/wiki/History_of_the_Church_of_England#Medieval_consolidation\" title=\"History of the Church of England\">Christian church</a> succeeded in allowing a person to leave part of his property to the church to use them as funds for its activities.\n</p><p>In <a href=\"/wiki/Law_of_the_Republic_of_Ireland\" title=\"Law of the Republic of Ireland\">law of the Republic of Ireland</a>, the Succession Act 1965 reduces freedom of testation by guaranteeing provision for the spouse and children of the deceased.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Freedom_of_testation&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><cite class=\"citation journal\">Nussbaum, Arthur (March 1937). \"LIBERTY OF TESTATION\". <i>American Bar Association Journal</i>. <b>23</b> (3): 183\u2013186. <a href=\"/wiki/JSTOR\" title=\"JSTOR\">JSTOR</a>&#160;<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//www.jstor.org/stable/25712364\">25712364</a>. <span style=\"font-size:90%; color:#555\">(Subscription required (<span title=\"The site requires a paid subscription to access this page.\" style=\"border-bottom:1px dotted;cursor:help\">help</span>))</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=American+Bar+Association+Journal&amp;rft.atitle=LIBERTY+OF+TESTATION&amp;rft.volume=23&amp;rft.issue=3&amp;rft.pages=183-186&amp;rft.date=1937-03&amp;rft_id=%2F%2Fwww.jstor.org%2Fstable%2F25712364&amp;rft.aulast=Nussbaum&amp;rft.aufirst=Arthur&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AFreedom+of+testation\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></li></ul>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1965/act/27/enacted/en/print#partix\">\"Succession Act, 1965\"</a>. <i><a href=\"/wiki/